comments.body: @mzelesky Will these dumps included deleted records? I assume they will. Do we need to enrich deleted boundwiths to add item / holding data from the host record?

@mzelesky If the incremental dump doesn't include one of the records for the boundwith, we'll have to pull that from the API to include it in the file. However, the SCSB records must include suppressed records. The API doesn't return suppressed records. I'm not sure there's a way to fulfill this requirement for that edge case.

@mzelesky we're considering whether it might work to create a nightly dump of all boundwith host and constituent records to reference as we create the scsb file. We messed around with sets a little, though, and couldn't figure out how to generate a dump like this. Do you think it is possible?
I haven't tried it but have you looked into https://knowledge.exlibrisgroup.com/Alma/Knowledge_Articles/Create_Users_Set_for_expired_patrons_based_on_Analytics? but this would be a one time set.

Availability not populating for all the search results

comments.body:
We could modify bibdata to call the holdings/ALL/items endpoint where the holding id is missing, or maybe when the holding id is missing and it's not ETAS.

Note that the end state is that ETAS is not a temp location, regardless.

The items would all have to be grouped by holding id and synthesized into the response.

The fact that we have so many ETAS items means there are millions of items with temporary locations. Without ETAS it might only be reserve items, maybe new book shelves, things that are temporarily in "the Annex".

Alternately, we use the index to store ETAS status.

orangelight.title: Location label changes on availability load

comments.body:
I have 2 solutions:
1.The first one is to display only the location and it will look like:
![Screen Shot 2021-04-21 at 4 45 22 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9905193/115619952-90b3f500-a2c2-11eb-8918-d98e13fbc898.png)

This will be identical with what is coming from the availability.js call and overrides the physical holding.

2.The second one is to display the library and the location. This will create a repetition of the library name since it is included in the external_name that we pull from alma.
![Screen Shot 2021-04-21 at 4 55 14 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9905193/115620119-c35ded80-a2c2-11eb-9ae8-b84b6d355ee3.png)

If we go with the second solution we will need to update the availability.js to include the library label in the response, which is ok. 
@mzelesky @kevinreiss what do you think?

This is the 3rd example from the screenshots https://catalog-alma-qa.princeton.edu/catalog?utf8=%E2%9C%93&search_field=all_fields&q=9912286923506421 from alma-qa using the availability.js

![Screen Shot 2021-04-21 at 5 07 00 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9905193/115621183-29974000-a2c4-11eb-88a5-d16e9e63e5bc.png)

and this is the same example with the physical holding not using javascript on alma-qa
![Screen Shot 2021-04-21 at 5 11 17 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9905193/115621549-acb89600-a2c4-11eb-907b-3f90a8c09793.png)
In my local I have reindexed the record with the correct updated location. This is why you dont see Recap but you see Mendel.

I would vote for only the location name. Will this pattern hold up for the default locations at each library? For the Firestone "stacks" we'd still want to see "Firestone - Stacks" rather than just "Stacks"
Yes it will be 'Firestone Library Stacks' as it appears in the first screenshot here https://github.com/pulibrary/orangelight/issues/2418#issuecomment-824358152
Sorry I missed that. I think the first approach works best. Less text > more text.
Thank you @kevinreiss
@axamei this one is deployed to staging
